{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17489095","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17489095"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T04:04:43+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T04:04:43+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"589"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"589","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/589"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.12,0.08,0.29,0.33,0.18]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"589"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103770"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"589","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/589"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"589"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86192"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"3915"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2232"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2287"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2292"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15662"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37009"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39770"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103770","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/103770"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 60-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a two-week history of feeling unwell, with abdominal discomfort and increased frequency of urination. He reports approximately eight voids per day with no nocturia and no pain on urination.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHe has a medical history of stage 2 lung cancer diagnosed 18 months ago and treated with surgical resection and adjuvant chemotherapy, hypertension, benign prostatic enlargement, and well-controlled bipolar affective disorder. His medications include perindopril, tamsulosin, and lithium.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 90/min, blood pressure 154/98 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. His BMI is 32 kg/m\u00b2. There is generalised abdominal tenderness to palpation but no percussion tenderness.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal: white cell count 11.8 \u00d7 10\u2079/L (4.0-11.0), sodium 140 mmol/L (135-145), potassium 4.5 mmol/L (3.5-5.0), random glucose 11.3 mmol/L (\u0026lt;11.1), corrected calcium 2.98 mmol/L (2.10-2.60), creatinine 110 \u03bcmol/L (60-110), PSA 5.0 \u03bcg/L (\u0026lt;4.0), and lithium level 1.0 mEq/L (0.6-1.0).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely cause of his symptoms?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Urinary tract infection","Benign prostatic enlargement","Type 2 diabetes mellitus","Hypercalcaemia","Lithium adverse effect"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with polyuria and abdominal discomfort in the context of previously treated lung cancer and significantly elevated corrected calcium of 2.98 mmol/L. \u003Cstrong\u003EHypercalcaemia\u003C/strong\u003E is the most likely cause of his symptoms, likely due to underlying malignancy. Hypercalcaemia of malignancy occurs through several mechanisms including parathyroid hormone-related protein (PTHrP) production, osteolytic metastases, or increased calcitriol production (seen in lymphoma). In lung cancer, PTHrP-mediated hypercalcaemia is most common. The classic symptoms include polyuria, polydipsia, abdominal pain, constipation, and confusion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUrinary tract infection\u003C/strong\u003E is unlikely given the absence of dysuria, normal temperature, and subacute presentation over two weeks. While prostatic enlargement increases UTI risk in men, the clinical picture does not support this diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBenign prostatic enlargement\u003C/strong\u003E is less likely as he lacks other lower urinary tract symptoms such as urgency, hesitancy, weak stream, or terminal dribbling. Additionally, he is already on tamsulosin for this condition, and the slightly elevated PSA is not clinically significant in this context. PSA levels do not strongly correlate with lower urinary tract symptoms (LUTS).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EType 2 diabetes mellitus\u003C/strong\u003E may be present given his BMI of 32 kg/m\u00b2 and random glucose of 11.3 mmol/L, but is unlikely to cause his current symptoms. Symptomatic polyuria from diabetes typically occurs with glucose levels consistently above 15 mmol/L, and would not explain his abdominal pain.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELithium adverse events \u003C/strong\u003Einclude\u003Cstrong\u003E \u003C/strong\u003Earginine vasopressin (AVP) resistance (previously nephrogenic diabetes insipidus), resulting in polyuria and polydipsia. However, he lacks nocturia (which would be expected with impaired urine concentration), and this differential would not explain his abdominal pain. While lithium can induce hyperparathyroidism, the hypercalcaemia in this case is more likely related to his lung cancer.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHypercalcaemia occurring in a patient with previously treated cancer should prompt investigation for metastatic disease. Hypercalcaemia of malignancy often portends poor prognosis, usually indicating advanced and often refractory cancer. Management includes treating the underlying malignancy where possible, intravenous hydration, bisphosphonates or denosumab, and sometimes glucocorticoids or calcitonin for temporary control.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Hypercalcaemia of malignancy typically indicates advanced disease and carries a poor prognosis.","Common symptoms of hypercalcaemia include polyuria, abdominal pain, constipation, and confusion (\u0027stones, bones, groans, and psychiatric overtones\u0027).","Parathyroid hormone-related protein production is the most common mechanism of hypercalcaemia in lung cancer."],"references":["Gastanaga VM, Schwartzberg LS, Jain RK, Pirolli M, Quach D, Quigley JM, et al. Prevalence of hypercalcemia among cancer patients in the United States. Cancer medicine (Malden, MA). 2016;5(8):2091\u2013100."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86192"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"589"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86192","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/86192"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-26T18:48:10+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-26T18:48:57+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"589"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103770"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"31","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/31"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf97","name":"Oncology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduatin